@database WBFADE10

@node "Main" "WBFade - Fader for the WB screen."

    @{b}WBFade 1.0@{ub} by @{b}Bozo@{ub} - Compiled @{b}960618@{ub}


    @{"IntroductionĀ" link "ID" 0}Ā- What is WBFade?
    @{"Installation " link "IN" 0} - You know what.
    @{"Usage       Ā" link "US" 0}Ā- How to use it.
    @{"History    Ā " link "HI" 0} - What it was like.


    Thanks to pOMAc for not letting me put shit in the main code!

    WBFade is @{b}FREEWARE@{ub} - use it any way you like.
    WBFade was programmed using Amiga E.
@endnode
@node "ID" "Introduction"

    WBFade is a program that grabs the WB palette before the WB
    has been opened, then it sets this to either a black or white
    palette and fades/nukes it to the real palette. It also has
    a RGB fading mode. Read more in @{"Usage" link "US" 0}

    Fade has been tested with the following configurations:

    A1200 28MHz 2Mb Chip 4Mb Fast
    A1200 14MHz 2Mb Chip

    @{b}Requirements@{ub}

    OS3.0+ and probably the AGA chipset.

@endnode
@node "IN" "Installation"

    The installation is quite simple. Just put a line like in the @{"Usage" link "US" 0}
    example JUST BEFORE LoadWB in your startup-sequence. It is VERY
    important that WBWait is started just before LoadWB.

    Remeber to always use RUN and a sufficent DELAY value. If the delay
    value is to small, the colormap could get messed up by WBStartup
    programs that allocates colors.
@endnode
@node "US" "Usage"

    There is a couple of arguments. They are SPEED, NUKE, R, G, B and DELAY.
    For a usage example:

    RUN >NIL: WBWFade S 2 B 100 D 18

    As you can see SPEED can be replaced by an S. The value is how
    many times $FF(256) should be devided and the result will be in
    how many steps the fade will operate. There is one VBL(frame)
    between each step, so a value of 2 would give you a fade that
    takes aprox. 2.5 seconds to complete. 2 is also the default
    value.

    The NUKE keyword can also be abbriviated with an N. Anyway, if
    you specify this boolean keyword the fade will start from color
    $FF(white).

    The three arguments R G and B are used to enable a special RGB
    fading mode. This is quite experimental at this stage though.
    Currently I am using an old routine witch does not follow
    any standards at all. It also is using lots of divisions.
    I will replace all fade routines with my asm fade routines in
    a later version of WBFade. I just haven't had the time to adapt
    them to E. Anyway, these arguments stands for the color to base
    the fade from. If you only specify one or two of them the last
    component(s) will not be faded i.e they will be the original
    color from the beginning. Just try this function out and you will
    get the idea. Note that RGB fading cannot be used in conjunction
    with NUKE.

    The D stands for DELAY and this value is very important. This is
    the time WBFade should wait before fading the palette. The value
    is in seconds and if you don't specify it it will default to 5
    seconds. As in the example my WB takes 18 seconds to fully load
    (horror).
@endnode
